At the close of the prior period, the Democracy Clock stood at 8:11 p.m., already deep into the danger zone. At the end of Week 42, it remains at 8:11 p.m., with only a tenth of a minute of net movement\'97too small to register on the public face. The stillness of the hand does not mean stillness in the system. It reflects a rough balance between accelerating executive lawlessness and meaningful, if outmatched, resistance from courts, states, and voters. The president\'92s open defiance of court orders on food aid, his stretching of war powers, and his mass pardons for election subversion all push the clock forward. Countervailing rulings on SNAP, judicial skepticism of emergency tariffs, and a wave of pro-democracy electoral outcomes pull it back. The result is a frozen dial over a churning mechanism.\
